ctors within these situations and also helps regulate conduct. Secondly, Unbound in War? shows that while international law can play important roles even in "high politics" areas like armed conflict, it is unclear whether the effect is ultimately attributable to an obligatory quality in law. Looking at the Korean War and the Afghanistan conflict, the ground-breaking arguments presented in Unbound in War? promise to advance interdisciplinary debates in both IR and IL, and contribute to broader policy discussions in these fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfghan War, 2001-zCanada. 0aAfghan War, 2001-zGreat Britain. 0aInternational lawzCanada. 0aInternational lawzGreat Britain. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953zCanada. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953zGreat Britain. 0aWar (International law). 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aBritain.  aCanada.  aKorean.  aarmed conflict.  aconflict.  adetainees.  ainternational.  alaw.  aprisoners of war.  arelations.  ause of force.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751798440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487517984/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles